Chlorophyllum palaeotropicum is very similar morphologically to C. shimogaense Sathe & S.M. Kulk. Both species have medium-sized, hemispherical to convex pilei covered with reddish-white to brownish-orange squamules composed of a trichodermal layer. Both species also possess clavate cheilocystidia and subglobose basidiospores. However, C. shimogaense possesses an umbonate pileus, basidiospores with an indistinct or absent germ pore, much smaller basidia (13-24 x 6-8.5 μm ) and no clamp connections (
Sathe et al. 1981 ( '1980' )
).
